name: pull up
instructor:
1-Find a sturdy bar or other object that is above you and within reach.

2-Stand directly beneath the bar or object with your arms extended upward, grasping the bar with both hands. Your palms should be facing away from you (overhand grip).

3-Engage your shoulder blades by pulling them down and back.

4-Begin to pull yourself up by bending your elbows and bringing your chest towards the bar.

5-Continue to pull yourself up until your chin is over the bar or object.

6-Slowly lower yourself back down to the starting position, keeping control of your descent.

7-Repeat for the desired number of repetitions.

*It's important to note that pull-ups require significant upper body strength, particularly in the back, shoulders, and arms. If you are just starting out or if you have limited upper body strength, you may need to work up to a full pull-up by performing modified versions or using resistance bands to assist you.

name: push up
description:
Beginner:
Set: 1-2 , Reps: 8-10 per set
Intermediate:
Set: 2-3 , Reps: 10-15 per set
Advanced:
Set: 3-4,Reps: 15-20 per set
instructor:
1-Start in a plank position with your hands slightly wider than shoulder-width apart and your feet together or slightly apart.

2-Engage your core, glutes, and legs to keep your body in a straight line from your head to your heels.

3-Lower your body towards the ground by bending your elbows, keeping your elbows close to your sides.

4-Continue lowering your body until your chest touches the ground or you reach a 90-degree angle at your elbows.

5-Push through your hands to straighten your arms and lift your body back up to the starting position.

6-Repeat for the desired number of repetitions.

**It's important to maintain proper form throughout the exercise to avoid injury and maximize the benefits. Keep your core and glutes engaged, and avoid letting your hips sag or pike up. Also, keep your elbows close to your sides to engage your triceps and prevent shoulder strain. If you're new to push-ups, start with a modified version by lowering your knees to the ground. As you become stronger, you can progress to the full push-up.

name: Overhead press
instructor:
1-Sit on a bench with your back straight, feet flat on the ground, and grip the barbell with an overhand grip, hands slightly wider than shoulder-width apart.

2-Rest the barbell on your upper chest, just below your chin, and lift it up to the starting position by pushing the barbell up with your arms, keeping your elbows slightly in front of the bar.

3-Press the barbell up and over your head in a straight line, extending your arms fully at the top of the movement.

4-Lower the barbell back down to your upper chest, and repeat the movement for your desired number of repetitions.

*It's important to keep your core engaged and your back straight throughout the exercise to avoid injury. Additionally, make sure to use a weight that you can lift comfortably without straining your muscles. If you're new to the exercise, start with lighter weights and gradually increase the weight as you become more comfortable and confident with the movement.

name: Barbell bent over row
description: 3-4 sets of 6-8 reps with a heavier weight that challenges you.
instructor:
The barbell bent over row is a weight training exercise that targets the back muscles, particularly the lats and rhomboids. Here are the steps to perform the barbell bent over row:

1-Stand with your feet shoulder-width apart and grip the barbell with an overhand grip, hands slightly wider than shoulder-width apart.

2-Bend your knees slightly and hinge forward at the hips, keeping your back straight and your core engaged. The barbell should hang directly below your shoulders.

3-Pull the barbell up towards your chest, keeping your elbows close to your body and your shoulders down and back.

4-Lower the barbell back down to the starting position, and repeat the movement for your desired number of repetitions.

*It's important to keep your back straight and avoid using momentum to lift the weight to prevent injury. Additionally, make sure to use a weight that you can lift comfortably without straining your muscles. If you're new to the exercise, start with lighter weights and gradually increase the weight as you become more comfortable and confident with the movement.

name: Barbell bench press
description:
set 1 : 10-12 reps
set 2 : 8-10 reps
set 3 : 6-8 reps
gradually increasing the weight with each set while decreasing the number of reps
instructor:
The barbell bench press is a popular exercise for targeting the chest, shoulders, and triceps. Here are the steps to perform the barbell bench press:

1-Lie flat on a bench with your feet firmly on the ground and your back pressed against the bench.

2-Grip the barbell with your hands slightly wider than shoulder-width apart, palms facing away from your body.

3-Unrack the barbell and bring it down towards your chest, keeping your elbows close to your body and your shoulders down and back.

4-Push the barbell back up towards the starting position, fully extending your arms.

5-Repeat the movement for your desired number of repetitions.

*It's important to keep your back flat on the bench, engage your core, and use proper form to avoid injury. Additionally, make sure to use a weight that you can lift comfortably without straining your muscles. If you're new to the exercise, start with lighter weights and gradually increase the weight as you become more comfortable and confident with the movement.

name: Barbell deadlift
description:
set 1:10-12 reps 
set 2: 8-10 reps 
set 3: 6-8 reps 
[[weight increases reps decrease]]
instructor:
1- Stand with your feet hip-width apart and your toes under the barbell. The bar should be positioned over the middle of your feet.

2- Bend down and grip the bar with both hands, using an overhand or mixed grip (one hand overhand, one hand underhand). Your hands should be shoulder-width apart.

3- Lower your hips, lift your chest, and straighten your back, keeping your core tight and your shoulders back.

4- Take a deep breath and brace your core. Then, drive through your heels and lift the bar off the ground, keeping it close to your body.

5- Lift the bar until you are standing upright, with your hips and knees fully extended.

6- Pause briefly at the top of the movement, then slowly lower the bar back down to the ground, keeping it close to your body.

Some tips to keep in mind:

- Use a weight that is challenging but allows you to maintain proper form throughout the exercise.
- Keep your core tight and your back straight throughout the movement to avoid unnecessary strain on your lower back.
- Keep the bar close to your body throughout the movement to avoid excessive stress on your lower back and maintain control of the weight.
- Exhale as you lift the bar off the ground and inhale as you lower it back down.
- If you experience any discomfort or pain, stop the exercise and consult a healthcare professional.

name: Reverse fly
description: 3 sets of 8-12 reps with moderate to heavy weights
instructor:
The reverse fly machine is a weight training exercise that targets the muscles of the upper back, particularly the rear deltoids and rhomboids. Here are the steps to perform the reverse fly machine exercise:

1-Adjust the seat of the machine so that the handles are level with your shoulders.

2-Sit on the machine with your chest against the back pad and your feet flat on the ground.

3-Grasp the handles with an overhand grip, and make sure your arms are fully extended.

4-Squeeze your shoulder blades together and pull the handles back towards your chest.

5-Pause for a moment at the end of the movement, then slowly release back to the starting position.

6-Repeat the movement for your desired number of repetitions.

*It's important to use proper form and avoid using momentum to lift the weight to prevent injury. Additionally, make sure to use a weight that you can lift comfortably without straining your muscles. If you're new to the exercise, start with lighter weights and gradually increase the weight as you become more comfortable and confident with the movement.

name: lever chest press
description: 2-3 sets of 12-15 reps with lighter weights.
instructor:
The lever chest press is a weight training exercise that targets the muscles of the chest, shoulders, and triceps. Here are the steps to perform the lever chest press:

1-Adjust the machine to fit your body size and choose the appropriate weight.

2-Sit on the machine with your back flat against the backrest and your feet firmly planted on the floor.

3-Grasp the handles of the machine with your palms facing down, and push the handles forward until your arms are fully extended.

4-Slowly lower the handles back towards your chest while keeping your elbows slightly bent and your shoulder blades squeezed together.

5-Pause for a moment at the end of the movement, then push the handles back to the starting position.

6-Repeat the movement for your desired number of repetitions.

*It's important to use proper form and avoid using momentum to lift the weight to prevent injury. Additionally, make sure to use a weight that you can lift comfortably without straining your muscles. If you're new to the exercise, start with lighter weights and gradually increase the weight as you become more comfortable and confident with the movement.

name: dumbbell lying extension face
description:
set 1 : 10-12 reps
set 2 : 8-10 reps 
set 3 : 6-8 reps
weight increases reps decrease.
instructor:
The dumbbell lying extension, also known as the dumbbell skull crusher or the lying triceps extension, is an exercise that targets the triceps muscles in the upper arm. Here's how to perform it:

1-Lie flat on a bench or mat with your feet on the ground and your head at the end of the bench.

2-Hold a dumbbell in each hand with your palms facing inwards and your arms extended straight up towards the ceiling.

3-Slowly lower the dumbbells towards your ears by bending your elbows, keeping your upper arms stationary.

4-Pause for a moment when your forearms are parallel to the ground, then extend your arms back up to the starting position by straightening your elbows.

5-Repeat for the desired number of repetitions.

* It's important to maintain proper form throughout the exercise to avoid injury. Keep your elbows close to your head and make sure to control the movement of the weights. Avoid locking your elbows at the top of the movement and keep your core engaged to protect your lower back.

name: sled 45в° leg press
description: 3-4 sets of 8-12 reps with a moderate weight
instructor:
1- Start by loading the appropriate weight plates onto the sled. Sit on the sled with your back flat against the backrest and your feet on the footplate.

2- Adjust the seat so that your knees are bent at a 90-degree angle when your feet are placed on the footplate.

3- Place your feet shoulder-width apart and firmly against the footplate.

4- Release the safety handles and slowly lower the footplate towards your body by extending your legs.

5- Pause briefly at the bottom of the movement, then push the footplate back up by flexing your legs.

6- Repeat for the desired number of repetitions.

Some tips to keep in mind:

- Keep your back flat against the backrest throughout the exercise to avoid unnecessary strain on your lower back.
- Avoid locking out your knees at the top of the movement to maintain tension in your leg muscles.
- Exhale as you push the footplate away from your body and inhale as you lower it back down.
- Use a weight that is challenging but allows you to perform the exercise with proper form.
- If you experience any discomfort or pain, stop the exercise and consult a healthcare professional.

name: Barbell Sit Squat
instructor:
1-Begin by positioning a bench behind you and standing with your feet shoulder-width apart, with the barbell resting on your traps (upper back) and your hands holding the barbell just outside your shoulders.

2-Take a step back and place your buttocks onto the bench behind you.

3-Keep your chest up, shoulders back, and core tight. This is your starting position.

4-Lower yourself down into a squat by bending your knees and pushing your hips back. Keep your weight on your heels and make sure your knees do not go over your toes.

5-Continue squatting down until your buttocks touch the bench behind you.

6-Pause for a moment at the bottom of the squat, then push through your heels to stand back up to the starting position.

7-Repeat for the desired number of reps.

- Make sure to maintain proper form throughout the exercise, with your chest up, back straight, and knees tracking over your toes. Start with a light weight and gradually increase the weight as you become more comfortable with the exercise.

name: lever seated hip abduction
instructor:
1- Sit on the lever seated hip abduction machine with your back straight and your feet flat on the footrests.

2- Adjust the weight to a level that is challenging but allows you to maintain proper form throughout the exercise.

3- Place your hands on the side handles and brace your core.

4- Slowly press your legs outwards, away from each other, using the sides of your glutes to drive the movement.

5- Pause briefly at the end of the movement, then slowly return your legs back to the starting position, keeping your movements controlled.

Some tips to keep in mind:

- Keep your back straight and your core engaged throughout the exercise to avoid unnecessary strain on your lower back.
- Focus on using the sides of your glutes to drive the movement and avoid using momentum or swinging your legs.
- Exhale as you press your legs outwards and inhale as you return them back to the starting position.
- Use a weight that is challenging but allows you to maintain proper form throughout the exercise.

name: dumbbell contralateral forward lunge
description:
Beginner: 2-3 sets of 10-12 reps on each side
Intermediate: 3-4 sets of 8-10 reps on each side
Advanced: 4-5 sets of 6-8 reps on each side
instructor:
1- Stand up straight with your feet hip-width apart, holding a dumbbell in your right hand.

2-Take a step forward with your left leg, bending your left knee and lowering your hips until your left thigh is parallel to the ground.

3- Keep your torso upright and your core engaged as you lunge forward.

4- Push off your left foot to return to the starting position.

5-Repeat the same movement with your right leg while holding the dumbbell in your left hand.

6- Alternate legs and continue lunging forward with each step, completing the desired number of repetitions on each side.

Some tips to keep in mind:

- Keep your core engaged throughout the exercise to maintain proper form and avoid unnecessary strain on your lower back.
- Keep your knees aligned with your toes and avoid letting them cave inward as you lunge forward.
- Keep your torso upright and avoid leaning forward as you lunge.
- Use a weight that is challenging but allows you to maintain proper form throughout the exercise.

name: Smith bent knee good morning
instructor:
1-Position the bar on the Smith machine to your desired height. Stand facing the machine with your feet shoulder-width apart and your toes pointing forward.

2-Step forward and place the bar on your upper back, just below your neck. Make sure to grip the bar with both hands to stabilize it.

3-Slowly bend forward at the hips while keeping your knees slightly bent. Keep your back straight and chest up.

4-Continue bending forward until you feel a stretch in your hamstrings, but make sure not to go too far that your back rounds.

5-Pause for a moment at the bottom of the movement, then slowly return to the starting position by extending your hips.

6-Repeat for the desired number of reps.

name: lever seated leg curl
description:
Beginner: 2-3 sets of 10-12 reps
Intermediate: 3-4 sets of 8-10 reps
Advanced: 4-5 sets of 6-8 reps
instructor:
1- Sit on the lever seated leg curl machine with your back straight and your legs extended in front of you.

2- Adjust the machine so that the footpad is positioned just above your heels.

3- Adjust the weight to a level that is challenging but allows you to maintain proper form throughout the exercise.

4- Place your hands on the side handles and brace your core.

5- Slowly bend your knees, lifting your heels towards your buttocks, while keeping your thighs on the seat.

6- Pause briefly at the end of the movement, then slowly return your legs back to the starting position, keeping your movements controlled.

Some tips to keep in mind:

- Keep your back straight and your core engaged throughout the exercise to avoid unnecessary strain on your lower back.
- Focus on using your hamstrings to lift the weight and avoid using momentum or swinging your legs.
- Exhale as you lift your heels towards your buttocks and inhale as you return them back to the starting position.
- Use a weight that is challenging but allows you to maintain proper form throughout the exercise.

name: Cool Down - Upper body
description: Repeat the cool down 1-2 times for 10-15 seconds or longer.
instructor: Remember to breathe deeply throughout the cool down exercises, and avoid pushing yourself to the point of discomfort or pain. The goal of a cool down is to gently ease your body back to its resting state, so take your time and listen to your body's signals.

name: Cable Wood Chop
instructor:
1-Set up the cable machine: Start by setting the cable machine to chest height and attaching a single handle to the cable.

2-Stand with your feet shoulder-width apart: Stand perpendicular to the cable machine with your feet shoulder-width apart and your arms extended out in front of you, holding onto the handle with both hands.

3-Rotate your torso: Keeping your arms extended, rotate your torso away from the cable machine and towards your opposite hip, pivoting on your back foot.

4-Bring the handle across your body: As you rotate, pull the cable handle across your body and towards your opposite hip, keeping your arms extended and your core engaged.

5-Return to the starting position: Slowly return to the starting position by reversing the motion, keeping your arms extended and your core engaged throughout the movement.

6-Repeat on the other side: Repeat the exercise on the other side by standing with your opposite side facing the cable machine.

- Remember to keep your core engaged throughout the exercise and to use a weight that challenges you without compromising your form. Start with a lighter weight and gradually increase as you become more comfortable with the exercise.

name: dumbbell romanian deadlift
instructor:
1-Begin by standing with your feet shoulder-width apart, holding a dumbbell in each hand with your palms facing your thighs.

2-Engage your core, keep your back straight, and shift your weight onto your heels.

3-Hinge at your hips and slowly lower the dumbbells towards the floor while keeping your knees slightly bent. Make sure to keep your back straight and avoid rounding your spine.

4-Lower the weights until you feel a stretch in your hamstrings, and then reverse the movement by squeezing your glutes and hamstrings to stand up straight.

5-Keep the weights close to your legs throughout the exercise and avoid any swinging or jerking motions.

6-Repeat for the desired number of reps and sets.

- Remember to start with lighter weights and gradually increase as you become comfortable with the exercise. Also, make sure to maintain proper form throughout the exercise to avoid injury and maximize the benefits.

name: Reverse Crunch
instructor:
1-Lie on your back on a mat or on the floor with your knees bent and your feet flat on the ground. Your arms should be by your sides, palms facing down.

2-Engage your core muscles and lift your legs off the ground, bringing your knees towards your chest. Your thighs should be perpendicular to the ground and your lower legs parallel to it.

3-Exhale and contract your abs to lift your hips off the ground and towards your chest, curling your tailbone off the floor.

4-Inhale and slowly lower your hips back down to the starting position, keeping your abs engaged throughout the movement.

5-Repeat for the desired number of repetitions.

*When performing reverse crunches, it's important to maintain proper form. Keep your lower back pressed into the ground and avoid using momentum to lift your legs. Focus on contracting your abs to lift your hips and keep your movements slow and controlled. If you have trouble maintaining proper form, you can modify the exercise by placing your hands under your hips for support or by performing the exercise with bent knees.

name: Hanging Leg Raise
instructor:
1-Hang from a pull-up bar with your arms straight and your palms facing away from you.

2-Engage your core muscles and lift your legs straight out in front of you, keeping them together and your toes pointed.

3-Exhale and lift your legs up towards your chest, bending your knees and curling your hips towards your ribcage.

4-Hold the peak contraction for a second, squeezing your abs and hips, then slowly lower your legs back down to the starting position.

5-Repeat for the desired number of repetitions.

*When performing hanging leg raises, it's important to maintain proper form. Avoid swinging or using momentum to lift your legs, and keep your movements slow and controlled. Focus on contracting your abs and hip flexors to lift your legs, and use your core muscles to control the descent. If you have trouble maintaining proper form, you can modify the exercise by bending your knees or by performing the exercise on a vertical bench or dip station.

name: bodyweight incline side plank
instructor:
1-Find a bench, box, or step and position yourself in an incline plank position, with your feet on the floor and your hands on the bench. Your hands should be directly below your shoulders, and your body should form a straight line from head to heels.

2-Shift your weight onto your left hand and foot, and lift your right arm straight up towards the ceiling. Your body should twist into a side plank position, with your right foot stacked on top of your left foot and your hips lifted off the bench.

3-Hold this position for 20-40 seconds, or for as long as you can maintain proper form. Focus on keeping your hips lifted and your core engaged throughout the movement.

4-Lower your right arm back down to the starting position, and then repeat the movement on the opposite side.

**When performing the bodyweight incline side plank, it's important to maintain proper form. Keep your body in a straight line from head to heels, and avoid letting your hips sag or rotate. Focus on engaging your obliques and core muscles to lift your hips and maintain stability. If you find the exercise too challenging, you can modify it by performing the movement from your knees instead of your feet.

name: Warm Up - Flutter Kicks
instructor:
1-Lie down on your back with your legs straight out in front of you and your arms by your sides.

2-Engage your core muscles and lift your legs a few inches off the ground. Your lower back should remain in contact with the floor.

3-Alternately raise and lower your legs rapidly in a scissor-like motion. Keep your toes pointed and your legs straight.

4-Continue for the desired number of repetitions or time.

*When performing flutter kicks, it's important to maintain proper form. Avoid arching your lower back and keep your core engaged throughout the exercise. You can modify the exercise by placing your hands under your glutes to support your lower back or by bending your knees slightly if you have trouble keeping your legs straight. You can also increase the difficulty of the exercise by holding a medicine ball or weight between your feet.

name: Warm up - Hip Bridge
instructor:
1-Lie on your back with your knees bent and feet flat on the ground, hip-width apart.

2-Place your arms by your sides, palms facing down.

3-Engage your core muscles and press your lower back into the ground.

4-Drive your heels into the ground and lift your hips up towards the ceiling, squeezing your glutes and engaging your core muscles.

5-Hold for 1-2 seconds at the top of the movement, then lower your hips back down to the ground.

*Remember to keep your core engaged throughout the exercise and avoid arching your lower back. Focus on using your glutes and hips to lift your body, rather than pushing up with your legs or lower back. By performing this exercise correctly, you can strengthen your glutes and hip muscles, which can help improve your posture and reduce the risk of lower back pain.

name: shoulder tap
instructor:
1-Start in a plank position with your hands shoulder-width apart and your feet together.

2-Keeping your core engaged and your body stable, lift one hand off the ground and tap your opposite shoulder with it.

3-Return your hand to the ground and repeat the movement with your opposite hand, tapping your other shoulder.

4-Continue alternating between shoulder taps for desired number of reps.

*Remember to keep your core engaged and your body stable throughout the movement. Avoid letting your hips sag or lifting them too high, and keep your neck in a neutral position to avoid any strain. If you find it difficult to maintain proper form, you can try widening your feet slightly for better stability.

name: weighted russian twist
instructor:
1-Sit on the floor with your knees bent and your feet flat on the ground. Hold a weight plate or dumbbell with both hands and extend your arms straight out in front of your chest.

2-Lean back slightly to engage your abs and obliques, and lift your feet off the ground, balancing on your sit bones.

3-Twist your torso to the right, bringing the weight towards your right hip. Keep your arms straight and your core engaged throughout the movement.

4-Pause briefly, then twist back to the left and bring the weight towards your left hip.

* This completes one repetition. Aim to perform 2-3 sets of 10-12 reps per set, resting for 30-60 seconds between sets.

- When performing the weighted Russian twist, focus on using your abs and obliques to initiate the movement. Keep your back straight and your neck in a neutral position throughout the exercise. Avoid using momentum or swinging your arms to complete the twist. Use a weight that is challenging but allows you to maintain proper form and control throughout the exercise.

- If you find the exercise too challenging, you can modify it by using a lighter weight or performing the movement without any weight. Alternatively, you can make the exercise more challenging by increasing the weight or adding a stability element, such as performing the movement on a stability ball or Bosu ball.

name: Cool Down - Seated Forward Bend
description: 30 seconds to 1 minute, and repeat it 2-3 times
instructor:
1-Sit on the floor with your legs extended straight out in front of you.

2-Inhale and raise your arms up overhead.
Exhale and bend forward from your hips, keeping your back straight.

3-Bring your hands to your feet or ankles, or use a yoga strap if needed.

4-Relax your neck and let your head hang down.

5-Hold the pose for several breaths.

6-Inhale and slowly come back up to a seated position.

name: barbell bench press
description:
first set :10-12 reps
second set : 8-10 reps
Third set 3: 6-8reps 
weight increases reps decrease.
instructor:
1-Start by lying down on a bench with your feet firmly planted on the ground and your back flat against the bench. Your head, shoulders, and butt should all be in contact with the bench.
2-Grip the barbell with both hands, with your palms facing away from your body and your hands shoulder-width apart.
3-Lift the barbell off the rack and hold it above your chest, with your arms fully extended.
4-Lower the barbell towards your chest, keeping your elbows close to your body and your wrists straight.
5-When the barbell reaches your chest, pause for a moment, and then press it back up to the starting position, fully extending your arms.
6-Repeat for your desired number of reps.
Some tips to keep in mind while performing a barbell bench press:

Keep your feet firmly planted on the ground and your back flat against the bench throughout the exercise.
Use a weight that is challenging but manageable for your fitness level.
Focus on maintaining good form throughout the exercise, keeping your elbows close to your body and your wrists straight.
Breathe in as you lower the barbell towards your chest and exhale as you press it back up.
If you experience any discomfort or pain while performing the exercise, stop immediately and consult a fitness professional.

name: Cable Pulldown
instructor:
The cable pulldown machine is a popular exercise that targets the back muscles, specifically the latissimus dorsi (lats). Here's how to perform a cable pulldown:

1-Start by sitting at the cable pulldown machine with your feet flat on the ground and your knees slightly bent.
2-Grip the bar with both hands, with your palms facing away from your body and your hands shoulder-width apart.
3-Lean back slightly, and engage your core to maintain good posture.
4-Pull the bar down towards your chest, bringing your elbows down and back towards your sides.
5-Pause for a moment when the bar is at chest level, and then slowly release it back up to the starting position.


Some tips to keep in mind while performing a cable pulldown:
Use a weight that is challenging but manageable for your fitness level.
Keep your movements smooth and controlled, avoiding any jerking or sudden movements.
Focus on engaging your lats throughout the exercise, rather than relying solely on your arms.
Breathe in as you pull the bar down towards your chest, and exhale as you release it back up.
If you experience any discomfort or pain while performing the exercise, stop immediately and consult a fitness professional.

name: Barbell full squat
instructor:
The barbell full squat is a compound exercise that targets the lower body, including the quads, glutes, and hamstrings. Here's how to perform a barbell full squat:

1-Start by standing with your feet shoulder-width apart, with the barbell resting on your upper back.

2-Grip the bar with both hands, keeping your elbows pointing down and your wrists straight.

3-Keeping your chest up and your core engaged, bend your knees and lower your hips down towards the ground.

4-Lower yourself down until your thighs are parallel to the ground or lower, making sure to keep your knees in line with your toes.

5-Pause for a moment in the bottom position, and then push through your heels to stand back up to the starting position.

6-Repeat for your desired number of reps.

Some tips to keep in mind while performing a barbell full squat:

- Use a weight that is challenging but manageable for your fitness level.
- Keep your chest up and your core engaged throughout the exercise.
- Focus on pushing through your heels as you stand back up to the starting position.
- Keep your knees in line with your toes throughout the exercise to avoid any undue stress on your knees.
- Breathe in as you lower yourself down into the squat, and exhale as you stand back up.
- If you experience any discomfort or pain while performing the exercise, stop immediately and consult a fitness professional.

name: smith seated shoulder press
instructor:
1-Start by adjusting the seat height of the Smith machine so that the bar is at shoulder height when you are seated.
2-Sit on the bench and position yourself underneath the bar, with your feet flat on the ground and your back against the bench.
3-Grip the bar with both hands, with your palms facing away from your body and your hands shoulder-width apart.
4-Lift the bar off the rack and hold it in front of your shoulders, with your elbows pointing down and your wrists straight.
5-Push the bar up and away from your body, extending your arms fully.
6-Pause for a moment at the top of the movement, and then slowly lower the bar back down to the starting position.
7-Repeat for your desired number of reps.

name: cable triceps pushdown
instructor:
1-Start by standing in front of the cable machine with your feet shoulder-width apart and your core engaged.
2-Attach a straight bar to the high pulley of the cable machine.
3-Grip the bar with an overhand grip, with your hands shoulder-width apart and your elbows tucked in close to your sides.
4-Keeping your upper arms stationary, push the bar down towards your thighs, extending your arms fully.
5-Pause for a moment at the bottom of the movement, and then slowly release the bar back up to the starting position.
6-Repeat for your desired number of reps.

name: kettlebell swing
instructor:
1-Start by standing with your feet shoulder-width apart and your toes pointing slightly outwards. Place the kettlebell on the ground in front of you.
2-Hinge at your hips and bend your knees slightly to pick up the kettlebell with both hands.
3-Stand up straight and swing the kettlebell back between your legs, keeping your arms straight and your core engaged.
4-Quickly thrust your hips forward and swing the kettlebell up to chest height, while maintaining a straight back and using the momentum to power the movement.
5-Allow the kettlebell to swing back down between your legs and repeat the movement for your desired number of reps.
Some tips to keep in mind while performing a kettlebell swing:

Use a weight that is challenging but manageable for your fitness level.
Focus on using your hips to generate power in the movement, rather than relying on your arms.
Keep your core engaged throughout the exercise to protect your lower back.
Keep your shoulders down and away from your ears.
Breathe in as you swing the kettlebell back between your legs, and exhale as you swing it up to chest height.
If you experience any discomfort or pain while performing the exercise, stop immediately and consult a fitness professional.

name: Standing mountain climbers
instructor:
1-Start by standing with your feet hip-width apart and your arms by your sides.

2-Lift your left knee towards your chest while simultaneously lifting your right arm straight up towards the ceiling.

3-Lower your left leg back down to the ground and bring your right arm back down to your side.

4-Repeat the movement on the opposite side, lifting your right knee towards your chest and your left arm straight up towards the ceiling.

5-Continue alternating sides, moving as quickly or as slowly as you'd like.

name: Rowing
instructor:
1-Begin by sitting on the rowing machine with your feet securely fastened into the footrests and your hands holding onto the handles.

2-Sit up straight with your shoulders relaxed and your core engaged.

3-Push off the footrests with your legs and begin to pull the handles towards your chest, keeping your elbows close to your body.

4-As you pull the handles towards your chest, lean back slightly, keeping your back straight and your abs engaged.
Once you've pulled the handles towards your chest, slowly extend your arms forward and bend your knees, sliding back towards the starting position.

5-Repeat this movement, pushing off the footrests with your legs, pulling the handles towards your chest, and then extending your arms and bending your knees to slide back to the starting position.

Some tips to keep in mind while using a rowing machine:

- Keep your movements smooth and controlled, rather than jerky or sudden.
- Focus on using your leg muscles to power the movement, rather than relying solely on your arms.
- Maintain good posture throughout the exercise, keeping your shoulders relaxed and your back straight.
-Experiment with different resistance levels and stroke rates to find a challenging workout that works for you.

name: Pigeon Pose
instructor:
1-Start in a tabletop position on your hands and knees, with your wrists under your shoulders and your knees under your hips.
2-Bring your right knee forward and place it behind your right wrist.
3-Slide your left leg back, straightening it out behind you, and make sure your left hip is facing the ground.
4-Slowly lower your body down onto your forearms or all the way down to the ground, depending on your flexibility.
5-You should feel a stretch in your right hip and glute. You can also gently press down on your right knee to deepen the stretch.
6-Hold the pose for 30 seconds to 1 minute, and then repeat on the other side.
Some tips to keep in mind while performing Pigeon Pose:

Be gentle and go slow if you are new to yoga or if your hips are tight.
Keep your hips square and facing forward.
Try to relax your body and breathe deeply throughout the pose.
If you experience any pain or discomfort, back off from the pose or come out of it altogether.
Pigeon Pose can be modified by using props such as a yoga block or blanket under your hips for support.

name: Bound Angle Pose / Butterfly Pose
instructor:
1-From a seated position, bring the soles of your feet together, close to your pelvis, allowing your knees to fall out to the sides.
2-Ground your sitting bones and lengthen your spine
3-Hold onto the outsides of your feet and press the soles of your feet towards each other.
4-If your body allows it, fold forward from the hips, keeping your spine long and your collar bones spread
5-Stay for 5 to 10 breathes
6-To come out of the pose, sit up straight again, lift your knees and straighten your legs

name: 3/4 sit-up
instructor:
1-Lie on your back on a mat or a comfortable surface with your knees bent and feet flat on the ground.

2-Cross your arms over your chest or place your hands behind your head with your elbows out to the sides.

3-Engage your core muscles and lift your head, shoulders, and upper back off the ground, raising your body about three-quarters of the way up towards your knees.

4-Hold the position for a few seconds, feeling the contraction in your abdominal muscles.

5-Slowly lower your upper body back down to the starting position.

6-Repeat for the desired number of reps and sets.

-Remember to keep your movements slow and controlled, avoid pulling on your head or neck, and breathe deeply throughout the exercise. Also, if you experience any discomfort or pain, stop the exercise immediately and consult with a fitness professional.

name: archer push up
instructor:
1-Start in a standard push-up position, with your hands slightly wider than shoulder-width apart.

2-Lower your body towards the ground, keeping your elbows close to your sides.

3-As you push back up, shift your weight to your right hand and rotate your body to the left, extending your left arm out to the side.

4-Lower your body back down towards the ground, this time shifting your weight to your left hand and rotating your body to the right, extending your right arm out to the side.

5-Continue alternating sides for 8-10 repetitions.

Some tips to keep in mind while performing archer push-ups:
Keep your core engaged throughout the movement to maintain stability and control.

Avoid letting your hips sag or pike up towards the ceiling.

Keep your elbows close to your sides as you lower your body towards the ground.

If this variation is too difficult, you can start by practicing standard push-ups and gradually work your way up to the archer push-up.

name: arm slingers hanging bent knee legs
assisted lying leg raise with lateral throw down
assisted triceps dip (kneeling)
description: 2-3 sets of 8-12 reps with a weight that provides appropriate assistance.
instructor:
Assisted triceps dips can also be performed using an assisted dip machine. Here's how to perform the exercise:

1-Adjust the weight on the machine to a level that provides the appropriate amount of assistance for your fitness level.

2-Stand on the footrests of the machine and grasp the handles with your hands, keeping your elbows close to your body.

3-Lower your body down by bending your elbows, keeping your chest up and your shoulders down.

4-Once your upper arms are parallel to the ground, push yourself back up to the starting position, squeezing your triceps muscles at the top of the movement.

5-Repeat for the desired number of reps.

*Remember to keep your core tight and your body upright throughout the exercise. You can adjust the weight on the machine to make the exercise easier or harder as needed. Also, be sure to use a weight that allows you to maintain proper form throughout the exercise.

name: band fixed back close grip pulldown
band one arm overhead biceps curl
band one arm standing low row
band side triceps extension
instructor:
1-Stand with your feet shoulder-width apart and hold the band with both hands, keeping your palms facing down and your arms extended straight at your sides.

2-Engage your core and keep your back straight as you lift the band up to shoulder height, making sure to keep your elbows tucked in at your sides.

3-Slowly extend your arms out to the sides, keeping your elbows in the same position, until your arms are fully extended.

4-Pause for a second, then slowly bring the band back to starting position, with your arms at your sides.

5-Repeat for the desired number of reps, then switch sides.


Some tips to keep in mind while performing the exercise:

- Make sure to keep your elbows tucked in at your sides throughout the movement.
- Use a band with enough resistance to challenge your muscles, but not so much that you can't maintain proper form.
- Keep your movements slow and controlled, focusing on using your triceps to extend your arms.
-Breathe steadily throughout the exercise, inhaling as you lift the band and exhaling as you extend your arms.

name: barbell lying back of the head tricep extension
barbell one arm side deadlift
description: 3 sets of 8-12 reps on each side
instructor:
1-Start by placing a barbell on the ground beside one foot.

2-Stand with your feet hip-width apart and your toes pointing forward.

3-Hinge forward at the hips and grasp the barbell with one hand, keeping your back straight and your core engaged.

4-Lift the barbell off the ground and stand up, using your leg muscles to drive the movement.

5-As you stand up, lift the barbell up to the side of your body, keeping your elbow close to your ribcage.

6-Pause briefly at the top of the movement, then slowly lower the barbell back down to the ground.

7-Repeat for the desired number of repetitions on one side, then switch to the other side.

Tip :
- Keep your back straight and your core engaged to avoid rounding or arching your back, which can increase your risk of injury. Choose a weight that challenges you without compromising your form.

name: barbell palms up wrist curl over a bench
barbell rear lunge
instructor:
1-Stand with your feet hip-width apart and hold a barbell across the back of your shoulders, gripping it with both hands.

2-Step back with one foot, placing it behind you, and lower your body into a lunge, bending both knees until your back knee almost touches the ground.

3-Keep your chest up and your core engaged as you push through your front foot to return to standing position.

4-Repeat on the other side, stepping back with the opposite foot and lunging down again.

5-Continue alternating sides for the desired number of reps.

name: barbell reverse grip bent over row
barbell reverse grip incline bench row
barbell seated twist
instructor:
1-Sit on a bench or a stable surface with your feet firmly planted on the ground and your back straight.

2-Hold a barbell behind your head with your hands slightly wider than shoulder-width apart and your palms facing forward.

3-Engage your core muscles and twist your upper body to the right, bringing the barbell towards your right hip.

4-Pause for a second and then slowly twist back to the starting position.

5-Repeat the movement, this time twisting to the left and bringing the barbell towards your left hip.

6-Alternate back and forth between the right and left sides for the desired number of reps and sets.

- Remember to keep your movements slow and controlled, avoid jerking the barbell, and breathe deeply throughout the exercise. Also, if you experience any discomfort or pain, stop the exercise immediately and consult with a fitness professional.

name: barbell squat jump step rear lunge
description:
2-3 sets of 8-12 reps on each leg.
- you can increase the weight or the number of reps.
instructor:
1-Start by standing with your feet hip-width apart, holding a barbell across your upper back.

2-Perform a squat by bending your knees and pushing your hips back, keeping your back straight and your chest lifted.

3-As you come up from the squat, jump explosively off the ground.

4-Land softly and step back with one foot, lowering your body down into a rear lunge.

5-Push through your front foot to return to standing, then step your back foot forward to return to the starting position.

6-Repeat the squat jump, then perform a rear lunge with the other leg.

- It's important to maintain proper form throughout the exercise. Keep your back straight, your core engaged, and your chest lifted. Choose a weight that challenges you without compromising your form.

name: bench dip on floor
description:
Beginner: 2-3 sets of 10-12 reps
Intermediate: 3-4 sets of 8-10 reps
Advanced: 4-5 sets of 6-8 reps
instructor:
1-Sit on the floor with your legs extended in front of you and your hands on the floor beside your hips, fingers pointing towards your feet.

2-Press your palms into the floor and lift your hips off the ground, straightening your arms as much as possible.

3-Keeping your elbows close to your body, lower your hips towards the ground by bending your elbows. Your elbows should form a 90-degree angle.

4-Push back up through your hands to return to the starting position.

5-Repeat for desired number of reps.

*Make sure to keep your shoulders down and your chest lifted throughout the exercise. Also, be sure to engage your triceps, chest, and core muscles during the movement.

instructor:

2-Sit on a bench or seat facing the cable machine with your feet flat on the ground and your back straight.

3-Grab the handles with both hands and bring them to the sides of your chest, keeping your elbows bent at 90 degrees. This is the starting position.

4-Press the handles forward, extending your arms and keeping your elbows slightly bent at the top of the movement.

5-Pause briefly at the top of the movement, squeezing your chest muscles.

6-Slowly bring the handles back to the starting position, keeping your elbows at a 90-degree angle.

7-Repeat for the desired number of reps.

*Remember to keep your back straight and your core engaged throughout the exercise. It's also important to use a weight that allows you to maintain proper form and control throughout the movement. Additionally, be sure to exhale as you press the handles forward and inhale as you bring them back to the starting position.

1-Hold a dumbbell vertically by one end, with both hands under the top of the weight.

2-Stand with your feet slightly wider than shoulder-width apart, toes pointing slightly outward.

3-Hold the weight close to your chest with your elbows pointing down.

4-Keep your chest up and your shoulders back as you lower your body down into a squat, pushing your hips back and bending your knees.

5-Lower your body until your thighs are parallel to the ground, keeping your knees in line with your toes.

6-Push through your heels to stand back up to the starting position.

2-Roll the barbell up your torso until it is securely resting on your hips.

3-Engage your glutes and hamstrings as you lift your hips up towards the ceiling, keeping your feet and shoulder blades firmly planted on the bench.

4-Pause for a second at the top of the movement, then slowly lower your hips back down to the starting position.

5-Repeat for the desired number of reps.

name: Barbell Hip Thrust
description:
set 1:10-12 reps 
set 2: 8-10 reps
set 3: 6-8reps 
weight increases reps decrease.
instructor:
1-Begin by placing a bench parallel to a barbell loaded with weights.

2-Sit on the bench and rest your shoulder blades against it. Your feet should be planted firmly on the ground, and your knees bent at a 90-degree angle.

3-Roll the barbell over your legs until it rests on your lap. Your hands should be holding the barbell slightly wider than shoulder-width apart.

4-Keep your chin tucked and your abs tight. Push through your heels and lift your hips up towards the ceiling.

5-Your body should form a straight line from your knees to your shoulders. Hold this position for a few seconds, then slowly lower your hips back down to the ground.

- Make sure to keep your back straight and avoid overextending your hips. Start with a light weight and gradually increase as you become more comfortable with the exercise.

4-Pause for a second, then slowly lower your hands back down to the starting position, with your elbows pointing forward and your hands at the sides of your head.

instructor:
1-Start in an all-fours position on the ground, with your hands under your shoulders and your knees under your hips.

2-Slowly move your knees out to the sides, wider than your hips, while keeping your toes touching.

3-Lower your hips down towards the ground, keeping your arms straight and your back flat.

4-You should feel a stretch in your inner thighs and hips.

name: alternate heel touchers
instructor:
1-Lie on your back with your knees bent and your feet flat on the ground.

2-Place your arms straight out to the sides of your body with your palms facing down.

3-Engage your core muscles and lift your head and shoulders off the ground.

4-Reach your left hand towards your left heel, while keeping your right shoulder off the ground.

5-Lower your left shoulder and head back down to the ground.

6-Repeat the same movement on the opposite side, reaching your right hand towards your right heel.

7-Continue alternating sides for the desired number of reps.

*Remember to keep your movements slow and controlled, avoid pulling your head with your hands, and engage your core muscles throughout the exercise. Also, make sure to breathe deeply and avoid holding your breath during the exercise. Additionally, if you experience any discomfort or pain, stop the exercise immediately and consult with a fitness professional.

close-grip push-up (on knees)
instructor:
The close-grip push-up is a variation of the traditional push-up that targets the triceps, chest, and shoulders. Here's how to perform the exercise on your knees:

1-Start on all fours on a yoga mat or a soft surface, with your knees hip-width apart and your hands shoulder-width apart, directly under your shoulders.
2-Walk your hands closer together so that your thumbs and index fingers are touching to create a diamond shape between your hands.
3-Extend your legs behind you, keeping your knees on the ground.
4-Engage your core and keep your body in a straight line from your head to your knees.
5-Lower your body down toward the ground, bending your elbows and keeping them close to your sides.
6-Pause when your chest is a few inches away from the ground.
7-Push back up to the starting position, extending your arms.
8-Aim to perform 2-3 sets of 8-12 repetitions, or as many as you can with good form.
9-Remember to breathe throughout the exercise and to keep your core engaged to protect your lower back.

Note: If you experience any pain or discomfort in your wrists or shoulders, modify the exercise by performing it on an elevated surface, such as a bench or step. You can also perform the exercise with your hands on dumbbells to decrease the strain on your wrists.

name: dumbbell alternating bicep curl with leg raised on exercise ball
dumbbell bicep curl on exercise ball with leg raised
bridge - mountain climber (cross body)
instructor:
1-Lie flat on your back with your knees bent and your feet flat on the ground.

2-Lift your hips up towards the ceiling, keeping your feet and shoulders pressed into the ground.

3-Hold the bridge position as you bring your right knee towards your chest and your left hand towards your right knee, crossing your body.

4-Return your right foot to the starting position and repeat on the other side, bringing your left knee towards your chest and your right hand towards your left knee, crossing your body.

5-Continue alternating sides for 10-12 repetitions.

name: cable kneeling crunch
instructor:
1-Set up the cable machine with a rope attachment at the highest pulley. Kneel down in front of the machine facing away from it and grasp the rope handles with both hands.

2-Position your arms so that your elbows are bent and your hands are next to your head, with the rope handles resting on your shoulders.

3-Engage your core and keep your back straight as you slightly lean forward, maintaining a neutral spine and neck position.

4-Exhale and crunch your torso forward, bringing your elbows down to your knees and contracting your abdominal muscles.

5-Hold the contraction for a moment, then inhale as you slowly return to the starting position, maintaining tension in your abs and core muscles throughout the movement.

6-Repeat for the desired number of reps.

*When performing the cable kneeling crunch, it's important to focus on using your abdominal and core muscles to initiate the movement. Avoid using your arms to pull the cable, and keep your neck in a neutral position throughout the exercise. Maintain proper form and avoid arching your back or leaning too far forward. If you find the exercise too challenging, you can reduce the weight or perform the exercise without the cable machine, using a medicine ball or other weight instead.

cable one arm press on exercise ball

cable rope lying on floor tricep extension
cable seated one arm alternate row
cable thibaudeau kayak row
instructor:
here's how to perform a cable Thibaudeau kayak row:

Stand facing a cable machine with your feet shoulder-width apart and your knees slightly bent.

Grab the handle with both hands, palms facing each other and arms extended straight out in front of you.

Twist your torso to the right, pulling the cable towards your right hip while keeping your left arm extended.

At the end of the movement, your right arm should be bent with your hand near your hip, while your left arm should be fully extended in front of you.

Slowly return to the starting position by straightening your right arm and twisting your torso back to center.

Repeat the movement, this time twisting your torso to the left and pulling the cable towards your left hip.

Alternate between right and left twists for desired number of reps.

Remember to keep your core engaged and your back straight throughout the movement, avoiding any excessive twisting or jerking motions. Focus on maintaining a smooth and controlled movement, and avoid using momentum to complete the exercise. If you're new to this exercise or have any shoulder issues, it's recommended to start with a lighter weight and gradually work your way up to heavier weights.

name: cable two arm curl on incline bench
dumbbell alternate biceps curl (with arm blaster)
dumbbell alternating seated bicep curl on exercise ball
dumbbell biceps curl
description: 2-3 sets of 6-8 reps (using cans or water bottles as weights)
instructor:
1-Stand with your feet shoulder-width apart and hold a dumbbell in each hand with your palms facing forward.

2-Keep your elbows close to your body and your back straight.

3-Curl the dumbbells up towards your shoulders by bending your elbows and contracting your biceps.

4-Keep your wrists straight and avoid swinging your arms or using momentum.

5-Pause briefly at the top of the movement, then slowly lower the dumbbells back to the starting position.

6-Repeat for your desired number of reps.

7-It's important to choose a weight that challenges you but allows you to maintain proper form throughout the exercise.

name: dumbbell cross body hammer curl v. 2
dumbbell decline bench press
instructor:
1-Lie on a decline bench with your feet secured at the bottom and your knees bent at a 90-degree angle.

2-Hold a dumbbell in each hand with your palms facing forward and your arms extended straight up over your chest.

3-Slowly lower the dumbbells towards your chest by bending your elbows, keeping your elbows tucked in at your sides.

4-Pause briefly at the bottom of the movement, then push the dumbbells back up to the starting position by straightening your arms.

5-Repeat for desired number of reps.

*Remember to engage your core muscles and maintain a stable position throughout the exercise. Also, avoid arching your back or lifting your feet off the bench during the movement.

name: dumbbell goblet squat
instructor:
1-Begin by standing with your feet slightly wider than shoulder-width apart. Hold a dumbbell vertically with both hands at chest level, with your elbows pointing down.

2-Keep your chest up, shoulders back, and core tight. This is your starting position.

3-Lower yourself down into a squat by bending your knees and pushing your hips back. Keep your weight on your heels and make sure your knees do not go over your toes.

4-Continue squatting down until your thighs are parallel to the ground or as low as you can go while maintaining good form.

5-Pause for a moment at the bottom of the squat, then push through your heels to stand back up to the starting position.

6-Repeat for the desired number of reps.

- Make sure to maintain proper form throughout the exercise, with your chest up, back straight, and knees tracking over your toes. You can increase the weight of the dumbbell as you become more comfortable with the exercise.

1-Sit on a bench or chair with your feet flat on the ground and hold a dumbbell in your right hand.

2-Raise your right arm overhead, keeping your elbow close to your head and your palm facing behind you in a reverse grip.

3-Keeping your upper arm stationary, bend your elbow to lower the weight behind your head until your forearm touches your bicep.

4-Pause briefly at the bottom of the movement, then extend your elbow to raise the weight back to the starting position.

5-Repeat for your desired number of reps, then switch to your left arm.

6-Remember to keep your core engaged and your back straight throughout the exercise to avoid any strain or injury.

7-Use a weight that challenges you but allows you to maintain proper form and complete the desired number of reps.

8-It's also important to perform the exercise in a slow and controlled manner to maximize the activation of your tricep muscles.

Remember to warm up before starting the exercise and to consult with a certified fitness professional if you have any concerns about proper form or technique.

name: dumbbell side Plank with rear fly
description:
Beginner: 2 sets of 10-12 reps
Intermediate: 3 sets of 8-10 reps
Advanced: 4-5 sets of 6-8 reps
instructor:
1-Lie on your side with your legs straight and your elbow directly under your shoulder.

2-Hold a dumbbell in your top hand, with your arm extended towards the ceiling.

3-Engage your core muscles and lift your hips off the ground, forming a straight line from your head to your heels.

4-Slowly lower the dumbbell towards the ground behind you, while keeping your arm straight.

5-Pause briefly when your arm is parallel to the ground.

6-Slowly lift the dumbbell back up towards the ceiling, while keeping your arm straight.

7-Repeat for the desired number of reps.

8-Lower your hips back down to the ground.

9-Repeat on the other side.

*Remember to keep your movements slow and controlled, avoid letting your hips drop or rotate, and engage your core muscles throughout the exercise. Also, make sure to choose an appropriate weight for the dumbbell and avoid using momentum to swing the weight. Additionally, if you experience any discomfort or pain, stop the exercise immediately and consult with a fitness professional.

dumbbell lunge
instructor:
1-Start by standing up straight with your feet shoulder-width apart and holding a dumbbell in each hand at your sides.

2-Take a big step forward with your right foot, while keeping your left foot in place.

3-Lower your body towards the ground, bending both knees and keeping your back straight. Your right knee should be directly above your ankle, and your left knee should be hovering just above the ground.

4-Push through your right heel to stand back up and return to the starting position.

5-Repeat the same movement with your left foot, taking a step forward and lowering into a lunge.

6-Continue alternating between right and left lunges for the desired number of reps or time.

Some additional tips for performing dumbbell lunges:

- Keep your core engaged throughout the movement to maintain good balance and stability.

- Focus on keeping your front knee aligned with your ankle and not letting it go past your toes.

- Use a weight that challenges you but allows you to maintain good form throughout the exercise.

- To make the exercise more challenging, you can increase the weight of the dumbbells, add more reps or sets, or try a walking lunge where you take multiple steps forward instead of alternating legs.
