ez barbell decline close grip face press
ez barbell reverse grip preacher curl
glute bridge two legs on bench (male)
incline scapula push up
instructor:
1-Find an incline surface, such as a bench or step, and position yourself facing towards it.

2-Place your hands on the incline surface, slightly wider than shoulder-width apart, with your fingers pointing forward.

3-Step back and lower your body towards the incline surface, keeping your elbows straight.

4-Once you've reached the bottom of the movement, focus on squeezing your shoulder blades together, as if you're trying to pinch a pencil between them.

5-Pause briefly at the top of the movement, then lower your body back down towards the incline surface.

name: kettlebell bottoms up clean from the hang position
kettlebell extended range one arm press on floor
kettlebell lunge pass through
instructor:
1-Hold a kettlebell in both hands at chest height, with your elbows bent and your palms facing each other.

2-Step forward with your right foot into a lunge position, bending your right knee and keeping your left leg straight.

3-As you lunge forward, pass the kettlebell under your right thigh to your left hand.

4-As you stand back up from the lunge position, pass the kettlebell back over your left shoulder to your right hand.

5-Repeat the lunge on the other side, stepping forward with your left foot and passing the kettlebell under your left thigh to your right hand.

6-Continue alternating sides for 8-10 repetitions on each side.

name: dumbbell decline one arm hammer press
dumbbell incline one arm hammer press on exercise ball
dumbbell incline one arm press on exercise ball
dumbbell kneeling bicep curl exercise ball
dumbbell lying on floor rear delt raise
dumbbell lying one arm press v. 2
dumbbell lying pullover on exercise ball
dumbbell one arm fly on exercise ball
dumbbell one arm french press on exercise ball
dumbbell one arm pullover on exercise ball
dumbbell one arm reverse fly (with support)
dumbbell one arm reverse grip press
dumbbell one arm reverse spider curl
dumbbell one arm seated hammer curl
dumbbell one arm shoulder press v. 2
dumbbell over bench one arm reverse wrist curl
dumbbell over bench revers wrist curl
dumbbell reverse grip incline bench two arm row
dumbbell seated bent over alternate kickback
dumbbell seated bent over triceps extension
dumbbell seated biceps curl (on stability ball)
dumbbell seated biceps curl to shoulder press
dumbbell seated one arm bicep curl on exercise ball with leg raised
dumbbell seated palms up wrist curl
dumbbell side lying one hand raise
dumbbell single leg deadlift
instructor:
1-Start by holding a dumbbell in your right hand and standing with your feet shoulder-width apart.

2-Shift your weight onto your left foot and lift your right foot slightly off the ground, balancing on your left foot.

3-Hinge forward at the hips, keeping your back straight and your right leg straight and lifted behind you. As you lower your torso, extend your right arm towards the ground, keeping the dumbbell close to your leg.

4-Lower your torso until your right leg and left arm are parallel to the ground or until you feel a stretch in your hamstring.

5-Use your left leg and glutes to push yourself back up to the starting position.

6-Repeat the movement for the desired number of reps before switching sides.

Some additional tips for performing dumbbell single-leg deadlifts:

- Keep your core engaged throughout the movement to maintain good balance and stability.

- Keep your standing knee slightly bent to avoid locking it out.

- Focus on keeping your back straight and not rounding your shoulders.

- Use a weight that challenges you but allows you to maintain good form throughout the exercise.

- To make the exercise more challenging, you can increase the weight of the dumbbell, add more reps or sets, or try balancing on an unstable surface like a balance pad or a bosu ball.

Remember to perform the exercise slowly and with control, especially if you are a beginner or if you have any balance issues.

name: dumbbell standing alternate hammer curl and press
dumbbell standing bent over one arm triceps extension
dumbbell hammer curl on exercise ball
dumbbell incline fly on exercise ball
dumbbell incline hammer press on exercise ball
dumbbell one arm hammer preacher curl
dumbbell one arm lateral raise with support
dumbbell over bench neutral wrist curl
dumbbell over bench one arm  neutral wrist curl
dumbbell palm rotational bent over row
dumbbell plyo squat
description:
set 1:10-12 reps 
set 2: 8-10 reps 
set 3: 6-8 reps 
weight increases while reps decrease.
instructor:
1-Stand with your feet shoulder-width apart, holding a dumbbell in each hand at shoulder level.

2-Lower into a squat, keeping your chest up and your knees in line with your toes.

3-As you come up from the squat, explode upwards into a jump, using the power from your legs to propel yourself off the ground.

4-Land softly back into the squat position.

Some tips to keep in mind while performing dumbbell plyo squats:

- Make sure to land softly and absorb the impact with your leg muscles, rather than landing with a hard impact on your joints.

- Keep your core engaged throughout the movement to maintain stability and control.

- Use a weight that challenges you but allows you to maintain proper form.

- Focus on pushing through your heels as you come up from the squat, rather than letting your knees cave inwards.

- If jumping is too difficult or not appropriate for your fitness level, you can perform regular dumbbell squats instead, focusing on lowering down slowly and powering up through your legs.

name: dumbbell pullover hip extension on exercise ball
dumbbell rear delt row_shoulder
instructor:
1- Begin by standing with your feet shoulder-width apart and holding a dumbbell in each hand, with your palms facing towards your body.

2- Hinge forward at your hips, keeping your back straight and your chest lifted. Your arms should be hanging straight down towards the floor, with the dumbbells just below your knees.

3- Next, bend your elbows and raise the dumbbells up towards your chest, squeezing your shoulder blades together at the top of the movement. Keep your elbows close to your body throughout the exercise.

4- Pause briefly at the top of the movement, then slowly lower the dumbbells back down to the starting position.

5- Repeat for the desired number of reps, then switch sides if necessary.

*Remember to maintain proper form throughout the exercise and focus on engaging your rear deltoids and upper back muscles. Start with lighter weights if you're new to the exercise, and gradually increase the weight as you become stronger and more comfortable with the movement.

name: dumbbell seated bent arm lateral raise
dumbbell seated one leg calf raise
dumbbell seated one leg calf raise - hammer grip
dumbbell seated one leg calf raise - palm up
dumbbell single leg deadlift with stepbox support
dumbbell standing biceps curl
instructor:
1-Stand with your feet shoulder-width apart and hold a dumbbell in each hand with your palms facing forward.

2-Keep your elbows close to your body and curl the dumbbells up towards your shoulders, exhaling as you lift.

3-Pause briefly at the top of the movement, squeezing your biceps muscles.

4-Slowly lower the dumbbells back down to the starting position, inhaling as you lower.

name: dumbbell standing inner biceps curl v. 2
dumbbell standing triceps extension
description:
Beginner: 2-3 sets of 10-12 reps
Intermediate: 3-4 sets of 8-10 reps
Advanced: 4-5 sets of 6-8 reps
instructor:
Here are the steps to perform the dumbbell standing triceps extension:

Stand with your feet shoulder-width apart and hold a dumbbell in both hands behind your head, with your palms facing upward and your elbows bent at 90 degrees.
Keep your upper arms close to your head, and your elbows stationary. This is your starting position.
Slowly straighten your arms, raising the dumbbell above your head until your arms are fully extended.
Pause for a second at the top of the movement, then slowly lower the dumbbell back to the starting position.
Repeat for the desired number of repetitions, then switch to the other arm if you are using one dumbbell.
It's important to keep your elbows in and close to your head throughout the movement, to isolate and engage the triceps muscles. Make sure to use a weight that challenges you while still allowing you to perform the exercise with proper form. If you experience any discomfort or pain, stop the exercise immediately and consult a fitness professional.

name: dumbbell waiter biceps curl
instructor:
1-Stand with your feet shoulder-width apart, holding a dumbbell with both hands with your palms facing up.

2-Lift your arms so that your elbows are at a 90-degree angle and your forearms are parallel to the ground. Your palms should still be facing up, and the dumbbells should be at shoulder level.

3-Keeping your upper arms stationary, slowly curl the dumbbells towards your shoulders by contracting your biceps.

4-Pause briefly at the top of the movement, then slowly lower the dumbbells back to the starting position.

5-Repeat for desired number of reps.

*Make sure to keep your elbows close to your body throughout the exercise and avoid swinging the weights or using momentum to lift them. Additionally, engage your core muscles to maintain good posture and stability.

name: exercise ball one leg prone lower body rotation
exercise ball one legged diagonal kick hamstring curl
ez barbell close grip preacher curl
ez-barbell standing wide grip biceps curl
dumbbell straight arm pullover
description:
For beginners: 2-3 sets of 8-10 reps per set
For intermediate lifters: 3-4 sets of 10-12 reps per set
For advanced lifters: 4-5 sets of 12-15 reps per set
instructor:
1-Lie down on a bench or stability ball with your head and shoulders supported, and hold a dumbbell in both hands with your arms extended straight up towards the ceiling.

2-Engage your core and keep your back flat against the bench or ball as you slowly lower the weight behind your head, keeping your arms straight and your elbows locked.

3-Keep lowering the weight until you feel a stretch in your chest and upper back, then pause briefly before pulling the weight back up to the starting position.

4-Exhale as you pull the weight back up, squeezing your chest and triceps at the top of the movement.

5-Repeat for the desired number of reps, making sure to maintain proper form throughout the exercise.

*Remember to choose a weight that challenges you but still allows you to maintain proper form, and to avoid arching your back or bending your elbows during the movement. You can also vary the exercise by using a single dumbbell, using a stability ball instead of a bench, or adjusting the angle of the bench or ball to target different muscles.

name: dumbbell tricep kickback with stork stance
exercise ball back extension with knees off ground
exercise ball on the wall calf raise (tennis ball between ankles)
ez bar reverse grip bent over row
Cool Down - hamstring stretch
description: each side 1-2 times.Hold the stretch for 15-30 seconds, then release and switch sides.
instructor:
1-Lie flat on your back with your legs extended straight out in front of you.

2-Bend your right knee and bring it towards your chest.

3-Place a strap or towel around the arch of your right foot, and hold onto both ends of the strap.

4-Straighten your right leg towards the ceiling, keeping your foot flexed.

5-Keep your left leg extended on the ground.

6-Pull the strap towards your body, bringing your right foot towards your head.

7-Keep your back flat on the ground and avoid lifting your head or shoulders.

name: hanging straight twisting leg hip raise
hyperextension
instructor:
The hyperextension exercise targets the lower back muscles, particularly the erector spinae, as well as the glutes and hamstrings. Here's how to perform a hyperextension:

1-Start by lying face down on a hyperextension bench with your feet secured under the footpads.
2-Position the pad at the top of the bench just below your hips, so that your hips are just off the end of the bench.
3-Cross your arms over your chest or place them behind your head.
4-Engage your glutes and lower back muscles to lift your upper body up off the bench until your body is in a straight line.
5-Pause for a moment at the top of the movement, and then slowly lower your body back down to the starting position.
6-Repeat for your desired number of reps.
Some tips to keep in mind while performing a hyperextension:

Use a weight or resistance level that is challenging but manageable for your fitness level.
Keep your movements slow and controlled, avoiding any sudden movements or jerking.
Focus on engaging your lower back, glutes, and hamstrings throughout the exercise.
Breathe in as you lower your body down towards the bench, and exhale as you lift your body up.
If you experience any discomfort or pain while performing the exercise, stop immediately and consult a fitness professional.

name: inverse leg curl (on pull-up cable machine)
jackknife sit-up
instructor:
1-Lie down on a mat with your arms extended behind your head and your legs straight.

2-Engage your core muscles and lift your arms and legs off the ground at the same time, keeping them straight and meeting in the middle of your body.

3-Touch your toes with your fingers and hold for a few seconds, feeling the contraction in your abdominal muscles.

4-Slowly lower your arms and legs back down to the starting position.

5-Repeat for the desired number of reps and sets.

- Remember to keep your movements slow and controlled, avoid pulling on your head or neck, and breathe deeply throughout the exercise. Also, if you experience any discomfort or pain, stop the exercise immediately and consult with a fitness professional. Additionally, if you have any pre-existing lower back issues, it may be best to avoid this exercise or modify it to a less strenuous variation.

name: kettlebell goblet squat
description:
Beginner: 2-3 sets of 10-12 reps
Intermediate: 3-4 sets of 8-10 reps
Advanced: 4-5 sets of 6-8 reps
Focus on maintaining good form and slowly increasing the weight and reps over time.
instructor:
1-Stand with your feet hip-width apart and hold a kettlebell with both hands, bringing it up to your chest.
2-Keep your elbows close to your body and your shoulders down and relaxed.
3-Engage your core and keep your chest lifted.
4-Lower your body down into a squat, bending your knees and pushing your hips back as if you're sitting in a chair.
5-Keep your weight in your heels and your knees in line with your toes.
6-Lower down until your thighs are parallel to the ground, or as low as you can while maintaining good form.
7-Pause briefly at the bottom of the squat.
8-Push through your heels to rise back up to standing, squeezing your glutes at the top.
9-Repeat for 8-12 reps, or as many as you can with good form.
10-Aim to perform 2-3 sets of goblet squats.
11-Remember to breathe throughout the exercise and to keep your core engaged to protect your lower back.

Note: If you experience any pain or discomfort in your knees or lower back, decrease the depth of your squat or choose a lighter weight. You can also try placing a block or a rolled-up towel under your heels to assist with the squat movement.

name: lever one arm lateral high row
frog crunch
instructor:
1-Lie on your back with your knees bent and the soles of your feet touching each other. Your knees should be pointing outwards.

2-Place your hands behind your head with your elbows pointing outwards.

3-Engage your core muscles and lift your head and shoulders off the ground, keeping your elbows pointing outwards.

4-Lower your head and shoulders back down to the ground.

5-Repeat for the desired number of reps.

*Remember to keep your movements slow and controlled, avoid pulling your head with your hands, and engage your core muscles throughout the exercise. Also, make sure to breathe deeply and avoid holding your breath during the exercise. Additionally, if you experience any discomfort or pain, stop the exercise immediately and consult with a fitness professional.

name: intermediate hip flexor and quad stretch
knee touch crunch
instructor:
1-Lie flat on your back on a mat or a comfortable surface with your knees bent and feet flat on the floor.

2-Place your hands behind your head, keeping your elbows out to the side.

3-Engage your core muscles and lift your head, neck, and shoulders off the ground.

4-Bring your right elbow towards your left knee, while keeping your right leg extended out straight and slightly lifted off the ground.

5-Lower your head, neck, and shoulders back down to the ground and then repeat the same movement with your left elbow towards your right knee.

6-Alternate back and forth between your right and left elbow while engaging your core muscles throughout the exercise.

7-Complete the desired number of reps and sets.

name: medicine ball catch and overhead throw
medicine ball chest push with run release
medicine ball close grip push up
modified push up to lower arms
otis up
instructor:
1-Lie on your back on a mat or flat surface with your arms extended overhead.

2-Keep your legs straight and together, and your toes pointed.

3-Lift your legs and torso off the ground simultaneously, keeping your arms extended.

4-Bring your legs towards your chest and touch your toes with your hands.

5-Lower your legs and torso back down to the starting position.

6-Repeat this movement for several repetitions to complete the Otis Up exercise. It is important to engage your core muscles throughout the movement and to focus on controlled movements.

name: side hip abduction
description: 3-4 sets of 20-25 reps on each side
instructor:
1-Lie on your side on a mat with your legs straight and your bottom arm extended out for support.

2-Place your top hand on your hip to help maintain proper alignment.

3-Engage your core muscles to stabilize your body.
Lift your top leg up towards the ceiling while keeping it straight.

4-Pause briefly at the top of the movement and then lower your leg back down to the starting position.

5-Repeat for the desired number of repetitions and then switch sides.

To increase the difficulty of the exercise, you can add ankle weights or a resistance band around your thighs. It's important to maintain proper form throughout the exercise and avoid arching your back or rolling your hips forward.

name: sled one leg calf press on leg press
cool down- calf stretch
instructor:
1-Find a wall or sturdy object to lean against.

2-Stand with your feet hip-width apart and about an arm's length away from the wall.

3-Step your right foot back, keeping your heel on the ground, and bend your left knee slightly.

4-Keep your right leg straight and press your right heel into the ground.

5-Lean forward into the wall, keeping your hands on the wall for support.

6-You should feel a stretch in your right calf muscle.
description: Hold the stretch for 15-30 seconds, then release and switch sides.

name: standing hamstring and calf stretch with strap
medicine ball chest push single response
power point plank
instructor:
1-Start in a high plank position, with your hands placed slightly wider than shoulder-width apart and your feet together.

2-Lift your right arm off the ground and extend it straight out in front of you, while simultaneously lifting your left leg off the ground and extending it straight out behind you.

3-Hold this position for 1-2 seconds, then return your right arm and left leg to the ground.

4-Repeat on the other side, lifting your left arm and right leg off the ground and holding for 1-2 seconds.

5-Continue alternating sides for 8-10 repetitions on each side.

name: resistance band leg extension
instructor:
1-Sit on the floor or on a chair with your legs straight out in front of you.

2-Loop a resistance band around the ball of your foots.

3-Slowly extend your leg straight out in front of you, keeping your knee as straight as possible.

4-Hold the position for a second, then slowly release and return to the starting position.

5-Repeat the movement for the desired number of reps before switching sides.

name: roller seated single leg shoulder flexor depresor retractor
self assisted inverse leg curl (on floor)
shoulder tap push-up
instructor:
1-Start in a plank position with your hands shoulder-width apart and your feet together.

2-Lower your body towards the ground by bending your elbows, keeping your core engaged and your back straight.

3-Push your body back up to the starting position.

4-Once you're in the starting plank position, lift one hand off the ground and tap your opposite shoulder with it. Return your hand to the ground.

5-Repeat the shoulder tap with your opposite hand.

6-Perform another push-up, then repeat the shoulder taps on both sides.

7-Continue alternating between push-ups and shoulder taps for desired number of reps.

*Remember to keep your core engaged throughout the movement, and avoid letting your hips sag or lifting them too high. Additionally, keep your neck in a neutral position and avoid letting your head drop or extend too far forward. If you're new to this exercise, start with a modified push-up by performing it on your knees until you build up enough strength to perform a full push-up with the shoulder taps.

name: smith one leg floor calf raise
smith reverse grip bent over row
smith standing behind head military press
twin handle parallel grip lat pulldown
weighted bench dip
description: 3 sets of 8-12 reps with moderate to heavy weights.
instructor:
Weighted bench dips are a great exercise for building upper body strength, especially in the triceps and chest muscles. Here's how to perform the exercise:

1-Sit on the edge of a bench or chair and place your hands on the bench next to your hips, fingers pointing forward.

2-Walk your feet out in front of you and lift your hips off the bench so that your arms are supporting your weight. This is the starting position.

3-Hold a weight plate between your thighs or attach a dip belt with a weight plate hanging between your legs.

4-Lower your body down by bending your elbows and keeping your chest up. Keep your elbows close to your body and your forearms perpendicular to the floor.

5-Once your upper arms are parallel to the ground, push yourself back up to the starting position, squeezing your triceps and chest muscles at the top of the movement.

6-Repeat for the desired number of reps.

*Remember to keep your core engaged throughout the exercise and to use a weight that challenges you but still allows you to maintain proper form.

name: weighted lunge with swing
instructor:
1-Hold a kettlebell or dumbbell with both hands in front of your chest, with your feet hip-width apart.

2-Step forward with your right foot into a lunge position, bending your right knee and keeping your left leg straight.

3-As you lunge forward, swing the weight between your legs, bending your knees slightly and hinging at the hips.

4-As you stand back up from the lunge position, swing the weight up to shoulder height, straightening your legs and extending your hips.

5-Repeat the lunge on the other side, stepping forward with your left foot and swinging the weight between your legs.

6-Continue alternating sides for 8-10 repetitions on each side.

name: medicine ball chest push from 3 point stance
medicine ball chest push multiple response
mountain climber
instructor:
1-Start in a high plank position, with your hands directly under your shoulders and your feet hip-width apart.
2-Engage your core and draw your right knee in toward your chest, keeping your foot off the ground.
3-Quickly switch legs, jumping your right leg back and bringing your left knee in toward your chest.
4-Continue alternating legs at a quick pace, as if you're running in place.
5-Keep your hips level and your shoulders stacked over your wrists throughout the movement.
6-Aim to perform the exercise for 30-60 seconds, or as many reps as you can in that time frame.
7-To modify the exercise, you can perform the movement at a slower pace, or step your feet in and out instead of jumping.
8-Remember to breathe throughout the exercise and to keep your core engaged to protect your lower back.

Note: Mountain Climbers are a high-intensity exercise that may not be suitable for everyone. If you have any injuries or health concerns, be sure to consult with a healthcare professional before attempting the exercise.

name: push-up (wall)
description:
beginners : 2-3 sets of 10-12 reps
advanced : 3-4 sets of 20-30 reps
instructor:
1-Stand facing a wall with your feet shoulder-width apart.

2-Place your hands on the wall at shoulder height and slightly wider than shoulder-width apart, with your fingers pointing upwards.

3-Step back a few feet from the wall so that your body is at a slight angle, but still relatively upright.

4-Engage your core muscles and lower your body towards the wall by bending your elbows, while keeping your body in a straight line from your head to your heels.

5-Pause for a second when your chest reaches the wall.

6-Push yourself away from the wall back to the starting position.

7-Repeat for the desired number of reps and sets.

- Remember to keep your movements slow and controlled, avoid arching your back or flaring your elbows, and breathe deeply throughout the exercise. Also, if you experience any discomfort or pain, stop the exercise immediately and consult with a fitness professional. Additionally, as you progress, you can increase the difficulty by moving your feet further away from the wall.

name: reclining big toe pose with rope
description: 3 sets , hold the pose 30 sec on each side
instructor:
1-Begin by lying on your back with your legs extended.

2-Loop a yoga strap or rope around the ball of your right foot and hold onto the ends of the rope with both hands.

3-Keep your left leg extended on the floor and your right leg extended up towards the ceiling.

4-Slowly begin to straighten your right leg by pulling on the rope with your hands. Keep your foot flexed and your leg as straight as possible.

5-If you feel comfortable, you can start to move your leg towards your head. Hold the position for a few deep breaths.

6-Slowly release the rope and lower your leg back down to the starting position.

7-Repeat the movement for the desired number of reps before switching sides.

name: resistance band seated biceps curl
instructor:
1-Sit on a chair or bench with your feet flat on the ground and your back straight.

2-Place the resistance band under your feet and grasp the handles with both hands, palms facing up.

3-Keep your elbows close to your body and your upper arms stationary.

4-Slowly curl the handles up towards your shoulders, squeezing your biceps at the top of the movement.

5-Pause briefly at the top of the movement and then slowly lower the handles back down to the starting position.

6-Repeat for the desired number of reps.

*Remember to keep your back straight and your core engaged throughout the exercise. Also, be sure to use a resistance band that provides appropriate resistance for your fitness level and training goals. If you need more resistance, you can use a heavier band or increase the tension on the band by holding it closer to the handles. Conversely, if you need less resistance, you can use a lighter band or hold it further down the band. Additionally, be sure to exhale as you curl the handles up and inhale as you lower them back down to the starting position.

name: Warm up - barbell one arm side deadlift
instructor:
1-Sit on a bench or chair with your back straight and your feet flat on the ground. Place a resistance band loop around your legs, just above your knees.

2-Engage your core and glutes, then slowly lift your knees apart, pressing against the resistance of the band.

3-Keep lifting until you feel a stretch in your outer hip muscles, then hold for 1-2 seconds.

4-Slowly release and bring your knees back together, still pressing against the resistance of the band.

Some tips to keep in mind:

- Keep your movements slow and controlled, focusing on engaging your hip abductor muscles throughout the exercise.
- Avoid leaning forward or backward or using momentum to lift your knees.
- You can adjust the tension of the resistance band by placing it higher or lower on your legs.
- If you feel any discomfort or pain, stop the exercise and consult a healthcare professional.

name: reverse plank with leg lift
instructor:
1-Sit on the ground with your legs extended out in front of you and your hands placed behind you, fingers pointing towards your toes.

2-Lift your hips off the ground, pressing your hands and feet into the floor. Your body should form a straight line from your head to your heels.

3-Engage your core muscles and lift your right leg off the ground, keeping it straight.

4-Hold for a few seconds, then lower your right leg back down to the ground.

5-Repeat with your left leg, lifting it off the ground and holding for a few seconds before lowering it back down.

6-Continue alternating legs for 10-15 repetitions.

Make sure to keep your hips lifted throughout the exercise and avoid letting them sag towards the ground. Keep your neck in a neutral position and focus on maintaining a strong and stable core.

name: roller seated shoulder flexor depresor retractor
side bridge v. 2
instructor:
1-Lie on your side with your elbow directly under your shoulder and your legs straight.

2-Engage your core muscles and lift your hips off the ground, forming a straight line from your head to your heels.

3-Extend your top arm towards the ceiling or rest it on your hip for added stability.

4-Hold this position for the desired duration, making sure to breathe deeply and engage your core muscles throughout.

5-Lower your hips back down to the ground.

6-Repeat on the other side.

- Remember to keep your movements slow and controlled, avoid letting your hips drop or rotate, and maintain a straight line from your head to your heels. Also, if you experience any discomfort or pain, stop the exercise immediately and consult with a fitness professional. Additionally, as you progress, you can increase the duration or add variations such as lifting the top leg or incorporating a side plank with movement.

name: single leg calf raise (on a dumbbell)
sled calf press on leg press
smith machine reverse decline close grip bench press
stability ball crunch (full range hands behind head)
resistance band hip thrusts on knees (female)
resistance band seated straight back row
single leg bridge with outstretched leg
smith machine decline close grip bench press
smith seated one leg calf raise
smith upright row
instructor:
The Smith upright row is a weight training exercise that targets the shoulders, upper back, and trapezius muscles. Here's how to perform it:

1-Stand in front of a Smith machine with your feet shoulder-width apart and your knees slightly bent. Grasp the bar with an overhand grip, hands shoulder-width apart, and palms facing down.

2-With the bar resting on your thighs, slowly raise the bar up towards your chin by lifting your elbows up and out to the sides. Keep your elbows higher than your wrists.

3-Pause at the top of the movement for a second, then slowly lower the bar back down to your thighs.

4-Repeat the movement for your desired number of repetitions.

*It's important to keep your back straight and your core engaged throughout the exercise to avoid injury. It's also important to use a weight that you can lift comfortably without straining your muscles.
description:
3 sets of 12-15 reps
It's important to note that when performing any exercise, it's crucial to listen to your body and adjust the weight and reps as needed to avoid injury and ensure proper form.

name: smith wide grip decline bench press
squat to overhead reach with twist
triceps dips floor
instructor:
1-Sit on the floor with your knees bent and your feet flat on the ground, with your hands placed on the ground behind you and fingers pointing forward.

2-Slowly lift your hips off the ground, straightening your arms and supporting your weight with your hands.

3-Lower your body towards the ground by bending your elbows, keeping your shoulders down and your elbows close to your sides.

4-Once your elbows reach a 90-degree angle, push back up to the starting position by straightening your arms.

name: weighted seated bicep curl  (on stability ball)
weighted triceps dip on high parallel bars
wide-grip chest dip on high parallel bars
weighted close grip chin-up on dip cage
weighted stretch lunge
instructor:
1-Begin in a standing position with your feet hip-width apart and holding a dumbbell or kettlebell in your right hand.

2-Take a large step forward with your left foot and lower your body into a lunge position. Your left knee should be bent at a 90-degree angle and your right knee should be hovering just above the ground.

3-As you lower into the lunge, simultaneously reach your right arm overhead towards the left side of your body. Keep your core engaged and your chest lifted.

4-Hold the stretch for a few seconds, then return to the starting position.

6-Alternate between sides for your desired number of reps or time.
